tional HIV Research Group, University of New South Wales), as cited in CASAM/APNSW, Partners for Prevention, UNAIDS, Sex Work and Violence. 101 For more see, Beattie et al., \u201cViolence against female sex workers in Karnataka state, south India\u201d; and Swain, Suvakanta N. et al. (2011), \u201cExperience of violence", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2cefa494-f666-4b64-8ecf-8d38cdad0843": {"__data__": {"id_": "2cefa494-f666-4b64-8ecf-8d38cdad0843", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/discussion-paper-linkages-between-violence-against-women-and-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Discussion paper: Linkages between violence against women and HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/discussion-paper-linkages-between-violence-against-women-and-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b5287d7957f17fee680f6d13476f484084805756262666140271c26ad9af7f9e"}, "3": {"node_id": "78e23436-1b98-4de3-84d6-e7314ab8a1b0", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/discussion-paper-linkages-between-violence-against-women-and-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5ea114dea6c4ce3244ad954f44786e44d2691070bd8a87ccd0e9a6ad8e7b3416"}}, "hash": "ef04a9d1e4ed6233600d6159b37ab585a5ececa8976b718a57774ff0c2aefc1d", "text": "and adverse reproductive health outcomes, HIV risks among mobile female sex workers in India,\u201d BMC Public Health vol. 11: 357\u2013367, as cited in CASAM/APNSW, Partners for Prevention, UNAIDS, Sex Work and Violence. 102 Decker, Michele et al. (2010), \u201cViolence victimisation, sexual risk and sexually transmitted infection symptoms among female sex workers in Thailand,\u201d Sexually Transmitted Infections, vol. 86: 236\u2013240, as cited in CASAM/APNSW, Partners for Prevention, UNAIDS, Sex Work and Violence. 103 CASAM/APNSW, Partners for Prevention, UNAIDS, 2012, Sex Work and Violence. 104 Tucker, Joseph, Xin Ren, and Flora Sapio (2010), \u201cIncarcerated sex workers and HIV prevention in China: Social suffering and social justice countermeasures,\u201d Social Science & Medicine, vol. 70 no. 1: 121-129, as cited in CASAM/APNSW, Partners for Prevention, UNAIDS, Sex Work and Violence. 105 Baral, S., Beyrer, C. et al. (2012), \u201cBurden of HIV among female sex workers in low-income and middle-income countries: A systematic review and meta-analysis, The Lancet, DOI:10.1016/S1473-3099(12). 106 UNDP (2012), \u201cSex Work and the Law in Asia and the Pacific.\u201d 107 For more, see The China Sex Worker Organization Network (2011), \u201cReport on the Impact of China\u2019s 2010 \u2018Strike Hard Campaign\u2019: A Crackdown on Sex Work\u201d; Alexander, P. (2001), \u201cContextual risk versus risk behavior: The impact of the legal, social and economic context of sex work on individual risk taking,\u201d Research for Sex Work, 4:3\u20135; WHO (2005), Violence Against Women and HIV/AIDS: Critical Intersections, Violence against Sex Workers and HIV Prevention,\u201d Information Bulletin Series, No. 3; and Human Rights Watch (2003), \u201cFanning the Flames, How Human Rights Abuses are Fueling the AIDS Epidemic in Kazakhstan,\u201d June 2003, vol.15, no. 4. See also Asia Calling (2010), \u201cBurmese Sex Workers Avoid Arrest with Bribes and not Carrying Condoms,\u201d at www.asiacalling.org/ km/special-reports/ sex-workers-stories-from-across-asia/1919-burmesesex- workers-avoid-arrest-with-bribes-and-not-carrying- condoms, NC Harm Reduction Coalition, 2012, Arrested for Carrying Condoms? Daily Kosas 30 Linkages between violence against women and HIV in Asia and the Pacific Drug use, violence, and HIV The estimated number of women who use drugs is increasing globally.108 In South-East Asia, women constitute approximately 10 percent of people who use drugs, with significant variations among countries. For example, in certain provinces within China, women comprise between 17 to 40 percent of all people who use drugs.109 Women face gender-specific risks, vulnerabilities, and consequences of their drug use as well as gender-specific barriers to information and access to harm reduction, violence survivor services, and sexual and reproductive health and HIV services.110 Gendered analysis of drug use shows that a \u201clarge proportion of women are introduced to drug use in sexual relationships and are more likely than men to share injecting equipment, in particular with their sexual partners.\u201d111 A 2008 study from China reported that more than 90 percent of women who inject drugs share equipment, particularly with their sexual partners.112 Women are often injected by others, and when this is their sexual partner \u201cthey are likely to use the needle after their partner, compounding their HIV risk.\u201d113 Further, gender power inequalities between women and men, and specifically women\u2019s dependence on their partners for drug use, as well as the threat of or actual violence restricts their ability to insist on clean needles, negotiate condom usage, and access harm reduction and HIV-related services. Studies114 also show that women who use drugs are more likely to transact sex to finance their and/or their partner\u2019s drug habit, leaving them at greater risk for HIV.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "78e23436-1b98-4de3-84d6-e7314ab8a1b0": {"__data__": {"id_": "78e23436-1b98-4de3-84d6-e7314ab8a1b0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/discussion-paper-linkages-between-violence-against-women-and-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Discussion paper: Linkages between violence against women and HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/discussion-paper-linkages-between-violence-against-women-and-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b5287d7957f17fee680f6d13476f484084805756262666140271c26ad9af7f9e"}, "2": {"node_id": "2cefa494-f666-4b64-8ecf-8d38cdad0843", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/discussion-paper-linkages-between-violence-against-women-and-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ef04a9d1e4ed6233600d6159b37ab585a5ececa8976b718a57774ff0c2aefc1d"}}, "hash": "5ea114dea6c4ce3244ad954f44786e44d2691070bd8a87ccd0e9a6ad8e7b3416", "text": "The control that some men who use drugs exercise over the drug use and habits of their female sexual partners can also result in the inability of female drug users to manage their drug use, including when to abstain or access treatment.115 Women who use drugs in the Asia-Pacific region face conditions of marginalization, criminalization, and police surveillance, which places them at heightened risk for violence and HIV. In many countries, possession of drugs or injecting equipment can lead to criminal sanctions, including imprisonment and involuntary detention in treatment centres \u2013 sites where there is a woeful lack of gender-sensitive services and where women are at particular risk for violence.116 A 2002 study in Sri Lanka points to women being at particular risk for rape, sexual exploitation, and sexual harassment during drug searches by law enforcement officials. 117 Where the possession of drugs is criminalized, women are unable to report police violence and harassment for fear of retribution. Even when perpetrators are not the police, studies from the region have indicated that women who use drugs are reluctant to report violence.118 108 Pinkham, S., Malinowska-Sempruch, K. (2007), \u201cWomen, harm reduction, and HIV\u201d (New York: Open Society Institute, International Harm Reduction Development Program), as cited in HAARP, \u201cUnderstanding", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9077b021-b4e1-4fb5-ba7b-ddbffe68f4a3": {"__data__": {"id_": "9077b021-b4e1-4fb5-ba7b-ddbffe68f4a3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/discussion-paper-linkages-between-violence-against-women-and-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Discussion paper: Linkages between violence against women and HIV in Asia and the Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/discussion-paper-linkages-between-violence-against-women-and-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "dd7f3b96413712d260353dd345c04e12f0f5aa9980e32e8e78369946e8a3f101"}, "3": {"node_id": "48e56ac1-81d7-41e7-ba15-02edb4adfc5d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/discussion-paper-linkages-between-violence-against-women-and-hiv-asia-and-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3a955970ed201fabdf0dcfb2a129414197e24f00c10aa40d79478f472b12492e"}}, "hash": "a9388cdf09c88b220edee1856cf2c36d67810e690ff188ea0a2dbf26c4898a5f", "text": "and responding to gender issues in substance use in South-East Asia.\u201d 109 Ibid. 110 United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime (2004), \u201cSubstance abuse treatment and care for women: Case studies and lessons learned\u201d; and Bassel et al., \u201cHIV and women who use drugs.\u201d 111 Hankins, C. (2007), \u201cSex, drugs, and gender: High time for lived experience to inform action,\u201d International Journal of Drug Policy, 19:95\u201396; as cited in HAARP, \u201cUnderstanding and responding to gender issues in substance use in South-East Asia.\u201d 112 Zhang, W. Y., Wu, J. Y. (2008), . \u201cThe characteristics of sexual behaviour, sexually transmitted diseases and HIV/AIDS of female intravenous drug users,\u201d China Journal of STD/AIDS Prevention and Control, 8:368\u2013370; as cited in HAARP, Understanding and responding to gender issues in substance use in South-East Asia. 113 Ibid., HAARP. 114 Hankins, \u201cSex, drugs, and gender\u201d; Gu, J., Wang, R., Chen, H. et al. (2009), \u201cPrevalence of needle sharing, commercial sex behaviors and associated factors in Chinese male and female injecting drug user populations,\u201d AIDS Care, 21:31\u201341; as cited in HAARP, \u201cUnderstanding and responding to gender issues in substance use in South-East Asia.\u201d 115 Family Health Inte